notesStmt.note: This manuscript is one of the relatively few illustrated Byzantine copies of the Acts and Epistles of the Apostles. It consists of three parts produced at different dates. The New Testament text with its accompanying prefatory material (known as Euthalian apparatus, after the name of its supposed compiler Euthalius) was copied in the early twelfth century. Then, lists of readings were added at two stages in the fourteenth and fifteenth centuries to facilitate their use in church. Some of the Epistles have lost the miniature that once marked their beginning. A couple of lost leaves were replaced in the sixteenth century.

msContents.textLang: The primary language in this manuscript is Greek, Ancient (to 1453).

msItem.title: List of liturgical readings from the Acts and Epistles
Menologion and Synaxarion
msItem.note: Fols. 314r-337r: list of Acts and Epistles readings for the movable feasts with troparia for feast days and psalm verses that accompany the lections; fols. 337v-360v: list of readings for the immovable feasts, again with troparia and psalm verses

support.p: Medium to heavy weight parchment for most of text, carefully prepared and with polished surfaces; fols. 267-268 of medium weight; fols. 314-360 lighter in weight and color

supportDesc.foliation: Pencil foliation in upper center of rectos; ink foliation in upper right corners of rectos (with 141 omitted)

handDesc.handNote: Copied by a single hand, except for the last entry on fol. 360v

Most of the manuscript is copied by a single hand, but the hand that copied fols. 267–268 also added the last entry of the Menologion on fol. 360v, and is therefore later; it is very similar to London, British Library Burney 49, ca. 1430.

decoNote.title: Title page of the Acts of the Apostles

note.p: The text of Acts opens here with a small image of Christ blessing the Apostles (see a similar image in Baltimore, Walters Art Museum Ms. W.522, fol. 1r), fitted within an ornamented headpiece. The text itself begins without a title, and the rubrics in the upper margin are now illegible.

decoNote.title: St. James the Apostle

note.p: St. James the Brother of the Lord is portrayed here as the author of the first Catholic Epistle. He wears episcopal vestments because the tradition identifies him as the first bishop of Jerusalem. The text next to his image is not the actual text of the Epistle but an explanatory preface to it, usually attributed to the obscure fourth-century Christian author Euthalius.

decoNote.title: St. Peter the Apostle

note.p: Peter is recognizable here from his white hair and rounded beard. He holds a small volume that evidently contains the text of his epistles.

decoNote.title: St. Peter

note.p: Unlike the image on fol. 98r, here Peter holds a scroll, a historically more accurate depiction of the original form of his epistle (letters would be rolled up, tied with a cord, and sealed).

decoNote.title: Title page of the First Epistle of John

note.p: John faces the beginning of his epistle's text, which is here entitled "Evangelic Theology of Christ." The rubric in the upper margin explains that this passage is read in church on May 8, the feast day of St. John the Apostle.

decoNote.title: Title page of the Second Epistle of John

note.p: This page contains the end of the preface to the Second Epistle of John, a short table of contents for it, and the beginning of the Epistle itself. Notice that the preface and chapters list are written in capital letters, unlike the biblical text, which is in regular minuscule script.

decoNote.title: Title page of the Third Epistle of John
Title page of the Epistle of Jude
Title page of the Epistle to the Romans

note.p: A red decorative line marks the beginning of the Pauline Epistles (which in Byzantine manuscripts usually follow the Catholic ones). St. Paul in the miniature is easily recognizable from his balding forehead and painted beard. Notice that the scribe has embellished the first letter of his epistle (the "P" of "Paul") with a small drawing of a human face.

decoNote.title: Title page of the First Epistle to the Corinthians
decoNote.note: St. Paul the Apostle and Sosthenes

note.p: This epistle was sent to the Corinthian Christians by St. Paul and Sosthenes: both are portrayed in the miniature which marks the beginning of its text.

decoNote.title: Title page of the Epistle to the Galatians
decoNote.note: St. Paul preaching to the Galatians

decoNote.title: Title page of the Epistle to the Ephesians

note.p: Notice the remains of a protective cloth curtain that once covered the miniature.

decoNote.title: Title page of the Epistle to the Philippians
decoNote.note: St. Timothy and St. Paul the Apostle

note.p: St. Timothy was, according to tradition, the first bishop of Ephesus and for this reason wears episcopal garments on this miniature, where he is portrayed as co-author of the Epistle of St. Paul. The two look up toward heaven, their hands raised in prayer.

decoNote.title: Title page of the Epistle to the Colossians
decoNote.note: St. Timothy and St. Paul the Apostle

decoNote.title: Preface to the First Epistle to the Thessalonians
decoNote.note: St. Paul preaching to the Thessalonians

note.p: On this page the miniature precedes the preface to the Epistle rather than the Epistle itself.

decoNote.title: Title page of the First Epistle to the Thessalonians
Title page of the Second Epistle to the Thessalonians
Title page of the Second Epistle to Timothy
Title page of the Epistle to Titus
Title page of the Epistle to Philemon

note.p: The miniature portrays Paul and Timothy as joint authors of the Epistle.

decoNote.title: Title page of the Epistle to the Hebrews
decoNote.note: St. Paul preaching to the Jews

note.p: A group of Jews, who wear no distinctive clothing, are being told by St. Paul about Christ, who is symbolically represented in heaven.

binding.p: Early twentieth-century binding; blind-stamped polished calf leather over thin rounded wooden boards; raised endbands; flat spine; parchment pastedowns and flyleaves

origin.origDate: Early 12th century CE (fols. 1-266, 269-313); 14th century CE (fols. 314-360); 15th century CE (fols. 267-268)
